## Building

To install the required dependencies and to build the elixir project, run:

```console
mix local.hex --force
mix do deps.get, compile
```

## Installation

If [available in Hex][], the package can be installed by adding `{{#underscored}}{{packageName}}{{/underscored}}` to
your list of dependencies in `mix.exs`:

```elixir
{{=<% %>=}}def deps do
  [{<%#atom%><%#underscored%><%packageName%><%/underscored%><%/atom%>, "~> <%packageVersion%>"}]
end<%={{ }}=%>
```

Documentation can be generated with [ExDoc][] and published on [HexDocs][]. Once published, the docs can be found at
[https://hexdocs.pm/{{#underscored}}{{packageName}}{{/underscored}}][docs].

## Configuration

You can override the URL of your server (e.g. if you have a separate development and production server in your
configuration files).

```elixir
config :{{#underscored}}{{packageName}}{{/underscored}}, base_url: "{{{basePath}}}"
```

Multiple clients for the same API with different URLs can be created passing different `base_url`s when calling
`{{moduleName}}.Connection.new/1`:

```elixir
client = {{moduleName}}.Connection.new(base_url: "{{{basePath}}}")
```

## Error handling

Generated operations return one of three shapes — note that `{:ok, _}` alone is
**not** a safe success match:

1. **Success statuses** decode into the mapped model struct:
   `{:ok, %{{moduleName}}.Model.SomeResponse{}}`.
2. **Error statuses declared in the OpenAPI spec** *also* return an `:ok`
   tuple, wrapping the spec's error model (an openapi-generator convention):
   e.g. a 400 comes back as `{:ok, %{{moduleName}}.Model.SomeErrorResponse{}}`.
   Match on the struct, not just the tuple tag:

   ```elixir
   case {{moduleName}}.Api.Things.get_thing(conn, id) do
     {:ok, %{{moduleName}}.Model.Thing{} = thing} -> {:ok, thing}
     {:ok, error_model} -> {:error, error_model}
     {:error, reason} -> {:error, reason}
   end
   ```

3. **Statuses the spec does not declare** (gateway 401/403s, proxy 502s, rate
   limits) return `{:error, %Tesla.Env{status: status, body: body}}`. When the
   response content type is JSON the body is decoded to a map; otherwise it is
   the raw binary.

Transport-level failures (connection refused, timeouts, DNS) surface as
`{:error, reason}` where `reason` comes from the configured Tesla adapter —
with the default Finch adapter, e.g.
`{:error, %Finch.TransportError{reason: :econnrefused}}`. If you swap the
adapter, the shape of `reason` changes with it.

## Live smoke testing

Unit tests mock the API from the spec — they cannot catch places where the
spec and the real server disagree. The SDK ships a live smoke-test scaffold in
`test/integration/live_test.exs` (tagged `:live`, excluded by default). Point
it at a real environment to verify auth, decoding, and error shapes:

```console
SDK_LIVE_BASE_URL=https://api.example.com SDK_LIVE_TOKEN=... mix test.live
```

